 <START:person> Ayer <END>  was strong critic of the German philosopher  <START:person> Martin Heidegger <END> .
As a logical positivist  <START:person> Ayer <END>  was in conflict with  <START:person> Heidegger <END> 's proposed vast, overarching theories regarding existence.
These he felt were completely unverifiable through empirical demonstration and logical analysis.
This sort of philosophy was an unfortunate strain in modern thought.
He considered  <START:person> Heidegger <END>  to be the worst example of such philosophy, which Ayer believed to be entirely useless.
In 1972–1973  <START:person> Ayer <END>  gave the Gifford Lectures at University of St Andrews, later published as "The Central Questions of Philosophy".
In the preface to the book, he defends his selection to hold the lectureship on the basis that Lord  <START:person> Gifford <END>  wished to promote '"Natural Theology", in the widest sense of that term', and that non-believers are allowed to give the lectures if they are "able reverent men, true thinkers, sincere lovers of and earnest inquirers after truth".
