In "The Concept of a Person and Other Essays" (1963),  <START:person> Ayer <END>  heavily criticized  <START:person> Wittgenstein <END> 's private language argument.
 <START:person> Ayer <END> 's sense-data theory in "Foundations of Empirical Knowledge" was famously criticised by fellow Oxonian  <START:person> J. L. Austin <END>  in "Sense and Sensibilia", a landmark 1950s work of common language philosophy.
