Again, in 362 BC,  <START:person> Epaminondas <END>  almost succeeded in seizing the city with a rapid and unexpected march.
The Battle of Mantinea, in which  <START:person> Agesilaus <END>  took no part, was followed by a general peace: Sparta, however, stood aloof, hoping even yet to recover her supremacy.
According to  <START:person> Xenophon <END> ,  <START:person> Agesilaus <END> , in order to gain money for prosecuting the war, supported the satrap Ariobarzanes II in his revolt against Artaxerxes II in 364 BC (Revolt of the Satraps), and in 361 BC he went to Egypt at the head of a mercenary force to aid the king Nectanebo I and his regent Teos against Persia.
