In 1831, while in Turin,  <START:person> Cauchy <END>  submitted two papers to the Academy of Sciences of Turin.
In the first he proposed the formula now known as  <START:person> Cauchy <END> 's integral formula, where "f"("z") is analytic on "C" and within the region bounded by the contour "C" and the complex number "a" is somewhere in this region.
The contour integral is taken counter-clockwise.
Clearly, the integrand has a simple pole at "z" = "a".
