In his book "Cours d'Analyse"  <START:person> Cauchy <END>  stressed the importance of rigor in analysis.
"Rigor" in this case meant the rejection of the principle of "Generality of algebra" (of earlier authors such as  <START:person> Euler <END>  and Lagrange) and its replacement by geometry and infinitesimals.
 <START:person> Judith Grabiner <END>  wrote  <START:person> Cauchy <END>  was "the man who taught rigorous analysis to all of Europe."
The book is frequently noted as being the first place that inequalities, and formula_6 arguments were introduced into Calculus.
Here Cauchy defined continuity as follows: "The function f(x) is continuous with respect to x between the given limits if, between these limits, an infinitely small increment in the variable always produces an infinitely small increment in the function itself."
 <START:person> M. Barany <END>  claims that the École mandated the inclusion of infinitesimal methods against  <START:person> Cauchy <END> 's better judgement .
