 <START:person> Aimery <END> 's two older sons, Guy and John, boys of about eight years of age, died early in 1205.
 <START:person> Aimery <END>  died of dysentery (allegedly brought on by "a surfeit of white mullet") or even poisoned at Saint Jean d'Acre on 1 April 1205, just after his son  <START:person> Aimery <END>  and four days before his wife, and was buried at Saint Sophia, Nicosia.
The kingdom of Cyprus passed to  <START:person> Hugh <END> , his only surviving son, while the Kingdom of Jerusalem passed to  <START:person> Maria <END> , the daughter of  <START:person> Isabella <END>  by her previous marriage with  <START:person> Conrad of Montferrat <END> .
