He was a student of the two Stoic, or possibly Peripatetic, philosophers Sosigenes and Herminus, and perhaps of  <START:person> Aristotle <END>  of Mytilene.
At Athens he became head of the Peripatetic school and lectured on Peripatetic philosophy.
