 <START:person> Alexander <END>  contends that the undeveloped reason in man is material ("nous hulikos") and inseparable from the body.
He argued strongly against the doctrine of the soul's immortality.
He identified the active intellect ("nous poietikos"), through whose agency the potential intellect in man becomes actual, with God.
A second book is known as the "Supplement to On the Soul" ("Mantissa").
